Problem 3 (Linear Regression using Pseudoinverse approach)¶

Generate a set of $200$ data points $\{x_i,y_i\}$ following equation in Question $1(e)$. Split this data into train and test subsets of $100$ points each, using the train_test_split method available in the sklearn library. Estimate the values of $a$ and $b$ using the pseudoinverse approach on the train set. Use these estimated values to make predictions for the test set. Compute the $MSE$ and the $R-squared$ measure. Experiment with different values of standard deviation ($\sigma$) and observe the impact on the values of $MSE$ and $R^2$.

Suppose our dataset is $D=\{(x_{i1},x_{i2},x_{i3},\cdots,x_{id},y^i) | 1 \leq i \leq n\}$, where $x^i=(x_{i1},x_{i2},x_{i3},\cdots,x_{id})$ is feature of $i^{th}$ training example and $y^i$ is the target value of that example.
The our linear regression model is $\hat{y_i}=f(x^i)=\beta_0+\beta_1*x_{i1}+\beta_2*x_{i2}+\cdots+\beta_d*x_{id}$.

Our objective is to find the values of the parameters $\beta=[\beta_0,\beta_1,\cdots,\beta_d]$ such that the error $$E=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i _i)^{2}$$ is minimized.

Such an $\beta$ can be found using pseudoinverse solution which is obtained using Least squares approach.
Let $A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & x_{11} & x_{12} & \cdots & x_{1d}\\ 1 & x_{21} & x_{22} & \cdots & x_{2d} \\ \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots\\ 1 & x_{i1} & x_{i2} & \cdots & x_{id} \\ \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots\\ 1 & x_{n1} & x_{n2} & \cdots & x_{nd} \end{bmatrix}$ , $\beta= \begin{bmatrix} \beta_0 \\ \beta_1 \\ \cdots \\ \beta_d \\ \end{bmatrix}$ and $Y= \begin{bmatrix} y_1\\ y_2\\ \cdots\\ y_i\\ \cdots\\ y_n \end{bmatrix}$.
Then the pseudoinverse solution is geiven by $\beta=(A^{T}A)^{-1}A^{T}Y$

Let's implement this.

In [32]:
a=2
b=3
n=200
x=np.linspace(-10,10,n)
y_hat=a*x+b
noise=np.random.randn(n)

def pseudo_inverse_soln(sigma):
    '''
    Returns parameters value using pseudo inverse approach.
    Also returns Mean square error and R-squared values for the model.
    '''
    # target values
    y=y_hat+sigma*noise
    # split the data into training and testing data
    x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(x,y,test_size=0.5,random_state=0)
    
    # Form the Y vector
    Y=np.array(y_train)
    Y=Y.reshape(-1,1)
    
    ## Forming the A vector
    X=np.array(x_train)
    X=X.reshape(-1,1)
    A = np.concatenate((np.ones((len(X),1)),X),axis=1)
    
    ## Pseudoinverse solution
    P=np.dot(np.linalg.inv(np.dot(A.transpose(),A)),np.dot(A.transpose(),Y))
    a=P[1]
    b=P[0]

    print("Value of 'a' using pseudoinverse is a =", a)
    print("Value of 'b' using pseudoinverse is b =", b)

    y_prediction=a*x_test+b

    print("Mean squared error is " ,mean_squared_error(y_test,y_prediction))
    print("R2 Score is ",r2_score(y_test,y_prediction))

Problem 4 (Linear Regression using Gradient Descent)¶

Recall our objective is to find the values of the parameters $\beta=[\beta_0,\beta_1,\cdots,\beta_d]$ such that the error $$E=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i _i)^{2}$$ is minimized. Such an vector $\beta$ can also be found using Gradient descent method. It invloves taking derivative of $E$ with respect to $\beta$ then update the value of $\beta$ repeatedly by using the equation $$\beta=\beta-\eta*\frac{\partial E}{\partial \beta}$$

When to use Gradient Descent?
When the dataset is huge, then the pseudoinverse solution will take a lot of space in storing the vectors $A,Y$. Thus the pseudoinverse solution becomes infeasible and time consuming. So we estimate $\beta$ using optimization algorithms using Gradient Descent.

def gradient_descent_simple_linear_regression(x,y,a,b,eta,iter):
    '''
    Perform gradient descent algorithm p=p-eta*gradient
    Hypotheses function y=ax+b
    p is the column vector(numpy array of shape (2,1)) containing the parameters 
    a and b and initial value of parameters and is of the form 
    p=np.array([[a],[b]])
    iter = number of iterations
    '''
    # initial parameter value
    p=np.array([[a],[b]])
    # all_p will store the value of the parameters after each gradient descent iteration.
    all_p=np.zeros((2,iter+1))
    all_p[:,0]=p[:,0]
    # Iterations
    for i in range(iter):
        # Calculate graident
        grad_a=(-2/n)*(((y-p[0,0]*x-p[1,0])*x).sum())
        grad_b=(-2/n)*(((y-p[0,0]*x-p[1,0])).sum())
        grad=np.array([[grad_a],[grad_b]])
        # Update parameter
        p=p-eta*grad
        # add to all_p
        all_p[:,i+1]=p[:,0]
    print(f"Final solution after {iter} iterations : a= {p[0,0]}, b={p[1,0]}")
    return p,all_p
In [38]:
def plot_trajectory(all_p):
    '''
    Plot the trajectory of the points obtained in gradient descent algorithm on 
    the contour plot of the error surface on (a,b) plane
    '''
    a_axis_width=abs(2-all_p[0,:]).max()+0.2
    b_axis_width=abs(3-all_p[1,:]).max()+0.2
    a_axis=np.linspace(2-a_axis_width,2+a_axis_width,101)
    b_axis=np.linspace(3-b_axis_width,3+b_axis_width,101)
    # Calculating Error
    E=np.zeros((len(a_axis),len(b_axis)))
    for i in range(len(a_axis)):
        for j in range(len(b_axis)):
            y_hat=a_axis[i]*x+b_axis[j]
            e=y-y_hat
            error=(e**2).mean()
            E[i][j]+=error
    a_axis,b_axis = np.meshgrid(a_axis,b_axis)
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(8,6)) 
    ax = plt.axes()
    ax.contourf(a_axis,b_axis,E)
    ax.plot(all_p[0,:],all_p[1,:],color='red',)
    ax.set_title('Trajectory of the solution obtained via gradient descent')
    ax.set_xlabel('a')
    ax.set_ylabel('b')
    plt.show()

Conclusion¶

  • Whether the iterations will converge or not heavily depends on our starting point and the value of .
    1. If is too small to start with, it will take higher number of iterations for convergence.
    2. If is too large it may result in oscillation or divergence of the parameters.
  • If our starting 'a' or 'b' value is far from original values a=2,b=3 then sometimes a little more than 100 iterations are required for convergence.
